INTRODUCTION TO OBJECT-ORIENTED PROGRAMMING (OOP)
1. Definition of OOP
Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) is a programming paradigm that uses classes and objects to design software systems.
It models real-world entities in code, making programs easier to understand and manage.
2. Purpose of OOP
To make programs organized and structured
To improve code reusability
To simplify maintenance and updates
OOP helps reduce repetition and makes large systems easier to develop and manage.
3. Key Components of OOP
Class
A class is a blueprint for creating objects.
It defines the structure and behavior that objects created from it will have.
Object
An object is an instance of a class.
It represents a real entity with actual values assigned to it.
Attributes
Attributes are variables that store data in an object.
Examples include name, age, or course.
Methods
Methods are functions defined inside a class.
They describe the actions that an object can perform.
4. Main Principles of OOP
Encapsulation
Encapsulation is the process of hiding internal data and controlling access to it.
It ensures data is accessed and modified in a controlled way.
Inheritance
Inheritance allows one class to acquire properties and methods from another class.
It promotes reuse of code and reduces duplication.
Polymorphism
Polymorphism allows methods to behave differently depending on the object.
It provides flexibility in how methods are used.
Abstraction
Abstraction hides complex implementation details and shows only essential features.
It simplifies interaction with objects.
5. Constructors in OOP
A constructor is a special method used to initialize objects.
In Python, it is defined using __init__.
It is automatically called when an object is created.
Functions of Constructors
Initialize object attributes
Assign values during object creation
Ensure the object is ready for use
Types of Constructors
Default constructor: does not take parameters
Parameterized constructor: takes values to initialize objects
Example
Python
class Student:
    def __init__(self, name, age):
        self.name = name
        self.age = age
6. Destructors in OOP
A destructor is a method used to destroy an object when it is no longer needed.
In Python, it is defined using __del__.
It is automatically called when an object is deleted or the program ends.
Functions of Destructors
Clean up resources
Free memory
Close files or connections
Example
Python
class Student:
    def __del__(self):
        print("Object destroyed")
7. Differences Between Constructor and Destructor
Constructor is called when an object is created
Destructor is called when an object is destroyed
Constructor initializes object data
Destructor cleans up resources
Both are important in managing the lifecycle of objects
8. Importance of Constructors and Destructors
Ensure proper initialization of objects
Help manage memory and system resources
Improve program efficiency and stability
Support proper object lifecycle management
9. Advantages of OOP
Promotes code reuse
Improves organization of programs
Simplifies debugging and maintenance
Supports scalability for large systems
10. Conclusion
Object-Oriented Programming is a powerful approach for building modern software systems.
It uses classes and objects to organize code effectively.
Constructors and destructors help manage object creation and destruction.
Understanding OOP is essential for developing efficient and maintainable programs.